// Nightshift Auth interface — vendor-neutral authentication plane.
//
// Auth is the multi-method authentication plane: each RPC group
// implements one auth method (OAuth 2.0 today; SAML, LDAP, custom
// token exchange, and other IdP flows may be added in future
// iterations). It is split out from `Secrets` (the KV +
// workload-auth plane) because operators may legitimately pick
// different backends for the two concerns — for example, HashiCorp
// Vault for encrypted KV alongside OpenBao's oauthapp plugin (or any
// future provider) for per-user OAuth credential storage and
// refresh.
//
// Today's surface:
//
//   * OAuth token dispenser. The per-user storage, refresh, and
//     dispense of OAuth 2.0 access tokens for MCP connectors. The
//     dispenser handles the authorization-code flow end-to-end and
//     exposes `GetOAuthToken(provider, user_id)` as the read-side
//     RPC the Config Dispenser calls at run start.
//
// Future auth methods will land here as additional RPC groups
// (each in its own section, with method-specific request/response
// messages and a verb prefix that names the method — e.g.
// `RegisterSAMLProvider`, `BeginLDAPBind`). New methods MUST NOT
// reuse OAuth-tagged messages or reuse the `OAuthToken` entity.
//
// Inbound bearer-token verification (the surface that authenticates
// HTTP/gRPC requests *into* nightshift-api) is NOT part of this
// proto; that lives entirely in `internal/auth/` (OIDCVerifier,
// StaticVerifier, WorkerVerifier) and is a reference-implementation
// concern, not a vendor-neutral contract.

